Parliament did not support an amendment to free Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian Parliament today rejected the proposal to repeal the amendment of the section of the Criminal Code condemning opposition leader Yulia Tymoshenko.
The amendment would open the doors to the release of the former prime minister, but parliamentarians rejected the proposal to reduce penalties for economic crimes in the second reading.
In October, Tymoshenko was sentenced to seven years in prison for the alleged signing of a disadvantaged agreement with Russia for Ukraine on the purchase of natural gas.
The ruling is not yet final, the court of appeal has an obligation to review it in December.
Tymoshenko was convinced that it was a political revenge of the regime, and even doubts have arisen in the West about the impartiality of the court.
The proposal to withdraw paragraph 365 of the Criminal Code, which sentenced the former prime minister, was supported by 147 deputies in the vote.
For its approval, 226 votes were required.
