IBM History: From Cheese Cutting Machine to Spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - originally it was a brand used in the branches of Canada and South America.
The basis that gave rise to the birth of IBM arises from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He possessed inventions such as the famous "signing clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired his supervisory board.
Flint signed the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help you with the management of the company.
The new leader overshadowed the IBM founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years Watson led the company, the turnover doubled to 9 million dollars and the great expansion of the company through the continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, almost after forty years occupying the boss’s chair, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM personnel and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
Meanwhile, in 1964 IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the computer standard of that time, came to market under the name IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering complete advice and services of high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid for the last three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, "a smarter planet".
It aims to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not yet been improved, for example in terms of transport and city management.
For the trade sector, IBM introduced not long ago the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the full business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 he opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country that had it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, the IBM ČR also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is in Prague. Here too, there is a world-renowned research team working with voice recognition.
