How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were in Czechoslovakia at that time only five authorized state travel agencies: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
The travel agencies of that time sold in most cases travel only to the socialist bloc, because travel to the West was very restricted.
Czech tourists therefore went on holiday to the beaches of the GDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union, (Sochi in Crimea in the Black Sea) to Bulgaria and Romania (both in the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
A positive exception was the period between 1962 and 1972, when you could travel to Yugoslavia, however, then the Yugoslav regime leaned west and the travel of Czech tourists was then quite restricted.
A great paradox of socialism was the fact that the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e., also the Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel freely and individually or even through the socialist countries.
If a citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter, if not, individual travel was not possible.
Travel agencies also offered trips to the West, but one was to stand in line with a sleeping bag and spend the whole night, or have "good acquaintances" in the agency.
Still not everything was won.
The so-called "promise of change" that was the condition for travel to the West, was not granted to the "politically unreliable people", who thus could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely convertible currency and, without guarantee of exchange, it was not possible to obtain the resources (the Western currency) to travel to the West.
The vast majority of Czechs spent their vacations in their own country, so there were a large number of cabins and summer houses, which the Czechs acquired. This custom still persists.
The way of traveling of the Czechs has undergone a real revolution since 1989.
While until 1989 for us it was not the more it is not going to spend the holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria, last year the Czechs made 4.5 million vacation trips to countries around the world.
It is a great paradox, of which we are no longer aware today, the fact that the destination currently favorite, Croatia, until 1989 could not travel freely, because it was part of the Yugoslavia of that time.
In the early 1990’s, visa waivers were imposed for travel to the neighbouring states of Western Europe, leading to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Vienna or Germany.
The Czechoslovaks, for a long time, didn’t look fed up with the excursions to the West, everyone wanted to see it for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris the groups of Czechs slept in the parks in tents, since our income of that time did not allow us to pay a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the Czechs of that time was to take the food (preserves, sausages, etc.) with it to save.
Another important moment was the introduction of the convertibility of the Czech crown, so our tourists could finally, after decades, freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living was rising and with it also average wages, which around 1997 caused an increase in the demand for travel.
With the increase in travel demand, agencies began, from 1997 onwards, to prepare travel using charter connections, which made travel prices incredibly lower compared to the past, thanks to the possibility of obtaining discounts for passenger volume.
By the end of the 90’s of the last century, the Czechs were already traveling visa-free to almost all developed countries, except the U.S., which further simplified our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary tourism happened as early as 2000, when it was organized, thanks to a huge demand, the first direct flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, and went to Thailand.
Since that year, direct charter flights with Czech tourists depart every year for distant and hot countries. This winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
The exotic countries are currently visited by about 100 thousand Czechs a year.
Another interesting moment of this era, symbolizing our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. eliminated visas for Czech tourists, making our country among the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008 the Czechs, for the first time in their history, have spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in their history, more than 15 thousand Czech kronor per head have been spent on abroad, including expenses on the stay site.
