Before becoming the far-right’s new face in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was simply another guy who aired his anti-immigration views online.
On Monday, Breivik, who admitted to carrying out a massacre in Norway in July, which left 77 dead, faced his first public court hearing.
While Breivik may have acted alone, he was far from being alone in cyberspace: He had spent most of the time he preceded his attack in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support right-wing groups on social media.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers wanted to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy - you just have to go to Facebook.
“We realized that it was not so difficult to reach them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recently published report on European digital populism by the British think tank DEMOS.
Facebook’s cache of personal information is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers could simply use the advertising tool to determine their desired demographics with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have been using for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of right-wing groups across Europe and then directed them ads, but instead of linking them to a new band or diet product, the ads invited users to complete a survey that asked about their educational level, attitudes toward violence and optimism about their own future.
Arriving via Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to study more than 10,000 followers of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – all without leaving the office.
“It’s a whole new way to do research,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results are not entirely surprising: Online supporters of right-wing groups tend to be young, men, and angry about immigration.
However, in a kind of twist, "those who combine their activism in line with offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind the computer screen."
DEMOS’ work is just one example of how Facebook is becoming an important new tool in the hands of scientists.
Research centers, medical researchers and political scientists are using the site to study everything from health issues to social trends as expressed in “Likes,” wall messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding an average of three pieces of content a day, Facebook’s “data supernova” is generating a research boom, driving the number of site named academic papers in the title to nearly 800% over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach with a folder on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to poll people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
“You’d have to go through the game, and they would never allow you access,” Bartlett says.
"Facebook removes all that - you go to them directly."
Others say the site could provide a way to identify and address health-social issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison and her colleagues found that college students who talked about their drunken exploits on Facebook had a significantly higher risk of drinking problems than students who remained silent on the issue.
Moreno suggests that student peers, such as residential counselors, could control the site and intervene to help a student post too many status updates with their drunkenness.
"You can't treat a problem if you can't diagnose it," said Dimitri Christakis, the co-author of Moreno and director of the Center for Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Seattle Children's Research Institute, the Washington Post said.
"We found a way to identify children at risk who would not otherwise be diagnosed."
Facebook is also constantly “punching” its own population to get data.
The Site’s Data Team has compiled statistics on the status of the relationship and Valentine’s Day, the expectation of voter turnout in the middle of the 2010 legislative period, and a National Happiness Index (mainly using the information that can be accessed – advocates of digital freedom long ago who argue that the site should make available to others its large amount of data for research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – the sacrifice for being able to play Scrabble with a friend thousands of miles away is to allow the site to mine your personal information.
But what happens when Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know about?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect their data offline, online it’s an open bar for everyone.
“I don’t think a lot of users have even thought about the fact that a researcher might be examining their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Laboratory, about a 2006 study he conducted with the public walls of Facebook students.
"As far as they were concerned, it was only between them and their friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research topic is being completely honest.
