7 Lessons from Steve Jobs's Lost Interview Showed in Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford - distinguishing the genius of technology as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been spent as a preview of a series of special projections in the biggest markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a flowchart yonki – a man who believed that many executives suffered “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s an enormous amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely was developing the TV series The Triumph of the Nerds over the dawn of the personal computer, and sat down for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively in his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringely's interview was used in Nerds, he said the interview originals disappeared during their transport.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full copy was discovered on VHS in the director’s garage.
This slightly reissued footage is the basis of Steve Jobs: The 68-minute lost interview, which hits Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known for hating in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
On four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between the questions and the answers – 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, seeking precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient because of Cringely’s questions, prompting him to go faster towards the most important issues or arguments.
Filmed before the Pixar era, the iPod or iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies do right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous assessments of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the anxious dreamer on the verge of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, it was and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
On how you learned to run a business:
"Over the years in business, I always asked, ""Why do you do things?" and the answers they give you invariably are, "Oh, that's just the way you do it."
No one knows why they do what they do, in business no one thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs takes his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting in detail.
Bewildered by the form in the costs were recorded - often starting with a "standard cost" that was made in the eye of a good bucket, and that then fit with a "variable" - developed an automated factory that ensured that they could determine the commercial costs in detail.
About the joke to the Pope:
Jobs narrates the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak - a device that allowed people to effectively hack into the phone company and make long distance calls for free.
It has been written extensively about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
It describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half-dozen times and yelling through the pay phone and going back a minute later to the next door’s pay phone,” Jobs says with a giggle.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We two didn’t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think that Apple would have ever existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost left, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and soliciting to speak to the Pope, while making his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling by phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched Bill Hewlett for the phone book and made a call.
Shortly after their 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my vision of what a company was and how well it treated its employees.”
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company's research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw "the first table computer ever made."
It was as big as a suitcase, had a small cathodic tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste my time with that machine and write programs for her.
About improvising innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the fly.
Soon in his career, as he dedicated himself to selling a handful of motherboards, a client asked if he could assemble the entire team.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to find out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he remembers the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they shouted at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost 300 dollars], and I got fed up and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for 15 dollars and that was totally reliable.
About big companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s rebirth, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble into his vision, and lose control of their market share.
"Say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better photocopiers and printers, so what?"
You have a monopoly on market share, so the company is not more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running companies and the people in charge of the products are expelled from the forum for decision making.
The genius of the products that led to that monopoly position rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened in Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90's...
They took the defeat of victory.
Innovation as an artistic expression:
"There's a tremendous amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the big idea evolves, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to make - some things you can't do that make electrons, glass makes them, robots make them, factories make them.
You have to keep 5000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjust them all at once...
In the end everything comes down to taste - it goes down to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then try to adapt those things to which you are doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been ashamed about stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who were coincidentally the best computer scientists in the world.
If it weren’t for computer science, I could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
