How to detect a lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and omnipresent deception and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each party accuses the other of lying.
Pennsylvania State University administrators have been accused of perjury for allegedly concealing reports that said a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "caught" with an open microphone asserting U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and online exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a fool of himself with his denials quickly slugged by irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign finance violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton by lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about cheating in school and college exams are widespread.
There have been cases where teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be best seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception are we?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere 10 to 200 times.
Surely, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or "the location of lies," is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: "I have you", the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the last six decades in prestigious universities that carried out in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been rebutted.
Liars do look into the eyes.
They don’t always stutter, babble, blush or restless.
It cannot be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation and times.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that the detection of deception is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from the research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more “self-oriented lies,” while women tell more “other-oriented” lies — usually to protect someone’s feelings — that married people lie less often than people who are not married (but the lies they often tell tend to be “huge”).
We also know that if you are perceived as a wrongdoer, others will feel less guilty in lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline."
It helps to provide benchmarks to then measure changes.
Observe the subject's posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
You better know if someone normally hits with the foot all the time so they don’t make unfair accusations when they see their feet pounding in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal, and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body by trying to remember their history, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward a way out, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview relief” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely show that the interview is over only to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used time spent while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distance language: "I didn't have sex with that woman...Miss Lewinsky" or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a bunch of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the answer a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
