This was the work of the Caleño who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A Lophoscopist from Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is key.
On November 4 a lophoscopist of the CTI of Cali went down in history as the man who confirmed the identity of the top boss of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", through the matching of his fingerprints.
Of the seven lophoscopists who work in the section of the CTI, that week it was the turn of "availability" to Eliazar González, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the area of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, González worked in municipalities of Chocó, where he often had to enter the jungle for more than five days to reach the place where the bodies that had to be identified were.
In 2000 he moved to the capital of the Valley and, after taking the corresponding courses, he specialized in lofoscopy, which is the study of friction skin, that is, of the palms of the hands and feet.
The week of the operation against alias Alfonso Cano told Eliazar that he would wear clothes for a minimum of three days.
Something big was waiting for you.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmyra.
He knew that he had to identify two bodies and that it was suspected that one of them was the man who was leading the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to carry the decacytillary card of Guillermo León Sáenz (his real name).
However, when he arrived with the research team at the site where the body was located, he did not recognize it because of his physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He was without a beard, dressed like a local peasant, no glasses and much thinner.
But the fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a transplanter and a flashlight, Eliazar compared the body’s fingerprints to those on the card.
His eye didn't fail him: it was "Alfonso Cano."
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was in charge of confirming to the Minister of Defense, Juan Carlos Pinzón, that he was the top head of the FARC.
In search of the footprint
For a Dactilloscopist from the Sijín de Cali the recognition made by President Juan Manuel Santos to Eliazar González, in the press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
Many people do not know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, which can become key in solving crimes.
Apart from the identification of corpses, the Lophoscopists support investigations into crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of the captured people.
When captured, many criminals file false or no papers.
We take the fingerprint and look for them in the database.
The investigator said that, in a case of theft, he had to remove a piece of wall from a house, because in that place the thief had supported his hand to take out a safe full of jewelry and money.
"The walls are difficult because they are not appropriate surfaces to get a fingerprint, but in that case we were able to get the fingerprint of the whole hand and identify the offender, who had participated in different thefts," he recalled.
Footprints can also rule out or reaffirm suspects in homicide cases.
They recently found a dead man, with bottles of liquor around him.
Through the investigation it was determined that a relative could be suspected of the crime and, indeed, a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Although this does not guarantee that he was the murderer, he does place him at the scene of the crime.
A CTI dactyloscoper explained that on objects "prints are taken out with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a transplanter or tape is used to lift them.
After this, the impressions are sent to the Asif, which is the criminal database, or to the Registry.
"The problem is that there are still many undocumented Colombians," the CTI expert said.
He clarified that not everything is as shown on the television program CSI.
Just as not everything that shines is gold, not everything that is touched becomes a mark.
However, if it can be used, if the respective check is performed.
