The government of the social democratic/Christian democratic grand coalition that is in power in Austria has decided on Tuesday to include in the Constitution a budget "golden rule" to reduce the public deficit and, thus, avoid a possible degradation of the sovereign note of Austria by credit rating agencies (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor, Werner Faymann, who announced this decision after a Council of Ministers, when the Austrian public debt reaches 74.6%, a figure much higher than the maximum limit of 60% set by the Maastricht Treaty, but clearly lower than the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced at a single level, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay 3,000 million euros more in interest each year," said Christian Democratic Deputy Foreign Affairs Chancellor Michael Spindelegger.
Austria thus responds to a request from the Brussels Summit to the euro area member countries on 26 October: in it, the Heads of State and Government called for the inclusion, before the end of 2012, of the reduction of the public deficit and the recovery of the balance of public accounts in the Constitution or in a Law with equivalent value.
The device adopted by the Austrian government is approaching the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
Before 2017, the structural public deficit should decrease each year by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) and, from 2017, the structural public deficit of the federal state should not exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional States, as well as communes, should present balanced budgets.
The objective is that, by 2020/2021, public debt is reduced under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
