Energy policy:
Facts must be worth more than dogmas
If there is one issue that cannot be addressed with short-term considerations or simply thinking about emotions, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting be time to reflect on such issues and the place of nuclear energy.
The discussion will only be useful if it studies all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7,000 million people on the planet, demographic evolution will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the increasing shortage of fossil resources to continue producing electricity continuously will have to be alleviated, not forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not modify any of these parameters.
Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear power.
That is not the case in Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, nor of Switzerland, which only aims to build state-of-the-art plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are moving forward with their projects.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of an interrupted power plant after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such a discourse.
The choice of Berlin will represent an increase in the price of electricity, a greater dependence on energy due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions due to the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
It must be meditated on the case of Denmark.
European champion in the wind sector, from which he obtains 30% of his electricity, is also one of the great users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; for this reason, his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are, respectively, 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear energy would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would detract from the wonderful declarations about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French refuse to pay and, in fact, do not express opposition in principle to that type of energy, according to the polls.
Remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and which can create non-relocationable jobs.
If France decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would mean the sacrifice of much of those SMEs and the loss of the 6,000 million euros per year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to operate sixty years, when the collapse of its manufacturer is planned?
To solve the equation of nuclear energy, it must be admitted that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no devilish source.
Areva’s development of low-CO2, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear power, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a safety authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of recognized professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred in normal operating conditions; it did not cause consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human failures.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two unprecedented natural disasters, which killed tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, just as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and cooperation between the security authorities, and the French and German operators and builders, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is studied by all the electric actors who want to build a power plant, the disruption of their construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them a free path to assume the leadership in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let the emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized starting from various points of view: the saturation of the police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "human rights country" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made headlines, with the Minister of the Interior (see the newspaper Libération of May 23) proclaiming from the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely economically analysed.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a bit of consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac fixed the orientation declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country that has about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was fixed by Michel Rocard explaining that France "can not take charge of all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and right shared fears of the invasion of the national territory by a crowd of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are considered to be a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is in the degree of generosity with which they act with respect to immigrants.
In its program, François Hollande is limited to including banalities, indicating that co-development will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be profitable electorally, but economically it comes out very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent work that summarizes the latest knowledge of immigration (How Mission Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among specialists on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
The limitation of immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears related to the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that immigrants can replace national workers, particularly the low-skilled, by pushing for their wages to be reduced.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are rather complementary than substitutes for national workers and exercise mainly professions in sectors with lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic and skilled workers in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks an anesthetists, complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the salaries and employment of nationals.
Given the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows represents a long-term increase in real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants contribute contributes to idea creation and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel laureates and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing on average 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at an age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of 150,000 euros to the public budgets on average throughout his life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go and look for the points of growth that he lacked "with his teeth".
These teeth, which discouraged immigrants, had exactly the reverse effect.
