This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more economically integrated Europe.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European popular sovereignty.
To build Europe, let’s make ourselves European.
"Contactless" chip cards are widespread
The world chip card show kicks off on Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, with an upbeat atmosphere.
In fact, 2011 should end with an 11% increase in global microprocessor card sales (bank cards, SIM card phones, etc.), with a total of 6,000 million units, according to Eurosmart cabinet calculations.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for common transportation or purchases by simply bringing the card closer to a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless chip cards will be sold worldwide, 320 million more than the previous year!
Its share should continue to increase in 2012 (580 million units are expected) and account for about 10% of the global chip card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe, which has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region, is gaining ground in the contactless payment sector.
Around 26 million Visa bank cards already have this function, which is accepted in 75,000 payment terminals.
In France, its beginnings are more modest: 400,000 contactless Visa cards are being used.
But large surfaces work for four.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless Pass MasterCard cards this year.
To get the upper gear, however, it is necessary for the banks to make them available to their customers.
"There are two large French establishments that have committed to systematically disseminate in the future, among their customers, bank cards equipped with the contactless system," announces Gérard Nébouy, CEO of Visa Europe France.
Banks try mobile phone payment
But it only constitutes a first stage towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Currently, there are few devices equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology, indispensable for transacting.
"They're lagging behind."
"But I should finally experience a real boom next year."
“We expect between 80 and 120 million units to be sold in 2012 worldwide,” explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks take the lead.
The bank Crédit agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test between December and next June in Caen.
The iPhones of around 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société générale has also affirmed yesterday that it is preparing the commercialization of an offer that allows its customers to pay without contact through their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is on the rise
Paris is concerned about the links between al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The links between the terrorist group al Qaeda in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect of Boko Haram, which were long suspected, have been confirmed.
On Sunday, Algerian Deputy Foreign Minister Abdelkader Messahel even claimed that Algiers already "has certainty."
“The way both organizations operate and intelligence reports show that they are cooperating,” he explained, without providing further details.
Paris seems to come to a similar conclusion.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have resumed the walkways.
Raptured in a Niamey restaurant by people related to Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory died the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators discovered several phone chips that belonged to the terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The study of the calls made indicates to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two numbers especially captured the interest of the researchers: one leads to a Nigerian who remained for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the birthplace of Boko Haram, and the other to a man who is supposedly close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is progress, but we must certainly wait to have more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"We have known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and that it is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months, such "supports" had become increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its operational modes, which now involve the use of kamikazes or explosive devices that are increasingly complex and of the same style as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, is since then pressuring Abuja to take into account the problems generated by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities, in fact, have long considered the group a community of ill-enlightened ill-deeding interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram (which means, in hausa, "Western education is a sin"), it incites the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes and demands strict respect for Sharia, while its militants are launched in the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are first of all oriented to churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram militants were particularly active and attacks against the police stations multiplied.
Abuja’s reaction was, as is often the case, widespread.
The army attacked the city and 800 were killed.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested in life, is killed in prison.
Since then, the sect has radicalized and abandons its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, he claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and then another in Abuja.
In June, Boko Haram again attacked Abuja, particularly against the police’s protected headquarters, with a suicide attack, the first of its kind.
In August, the United Nations headquarters became its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa, which would range from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria, disturbs all security specialists.
While Aqmi has attacked Mali and Niger and that the Somalis of Al-Chebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram emerges as a new threat in the center of the continent.
Last week, during a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned him against Boko Haram and said he was willing to “share all the information.”
The World According to Republican Presidency Candidates
In relation to China, with Iran and with the help of Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete in simplicity and lack of knowledge.
A crisis-weakened America, can it manage a complex world with simple or even simplistic ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might think they are.
For a few days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and the other candidates have been making more thunderous statements and shortcuts on foreign policy, traditionally a strong point for Republicans.
The slogans, often unfounded, about China, Iran, aid to Israel, are spread.
Mitt Romney, the best-placed candidate in the “Grand Old Party” nomination, has threatened to bring the Chinese to the WTO and denounce them “for manipulation of their currency,” a key issue in an America exasperated by the migration of entire fragments of its sector to Asia.
