But the attacks are not easy for them.
The population rather positively judges Obama’s national security balance, which ended with bin Laden.
From Iraq, he is wary of the military interventions that generate a sinking.
And, arguing that we need to economically rebuild America to resurrect its leadership, Obama gives the impression of being fairer.
The Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, participated on the shores of the Baltic, between the music of the orchestra and a delicate buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and her counterpart from the Netherlands, Mark Rutte, have turned the valve flyer that controls the Russian gas inflow into the Western European network together.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 million cubic meters of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first had 1,224 km that connects the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube should be completed at the end of 2012 which will allow a total of 55,000 million cubic meters of gas, that is, sufficient to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube along the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work features victory airs.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow gas to be supplied directly to Germany, avoiding the land course by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close it access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of the energy Europe, given that the project has generated a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has known, in just five years, to make its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, large gas consumers and with increasingly limited reserves triumph.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically," François Fillon confirmed during the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating the extent to which the large contracts in the gas sector are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles on the faces of Gazprom managers, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The underwater tube is made of cement-coated steel to protect against ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at an average of 200 m deep.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
"It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extreme measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted in its entire length: neither by valves, nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in the waters of Sweden, but those responsible for the project gave up on the project to see that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state society to settle permanently at sea off its coast.
"In case of failure, we will interrupt the passage of the gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But the builders consider it unlikely that there will be a leak, since they have foreseen joints that, according to forecasts, will have a leak every 100,000 years.
The control of the state of the pipeline is guaranteed by an underwater robot, carried by a ship, which performs external inspections, as well as by means of a device circulating inside the pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced into the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it supplies accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for fifty years without the need for any repair.
The circulation of the gas is guaranteed simply by the pressure.
At first it is 200 bars and, at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the stakes.
To her, the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, responsible for building and exploiting the pipeline.
It is based in Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is especially favourable.
Afterwards, Gazprom rented to that company, for a period of twenty-five years renewable, all gas transport capacities.
“Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” Jens Müller says.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline has been carried out in 30% with the contribution of shareholders and 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident that they will not exceed their investment, since Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a brand book.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people the taste for writing.
He has an air of adventure, hours of writing by candlelight.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, the current-looking Moleskine notebooks were born in 1997.
The Italian company Mode Mode, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, was responsible for the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the stools.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who since then became responsible for the brand in Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, reaching a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
Far from it has been the confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the profile of the buyer, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-spirited and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had twelve workers in its beginnings, now owns about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops of the center of the cities, and has managed to impose his identity.
"We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the rise of emails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural firm goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also launched a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in autumn 2006, Mode Mode was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, currently Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
About 19% of disabled people are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolved public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among disabled people doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the population as a whole.
Daunting?
“No,” says Éric Blanchet, managing director of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past fifteen years is considerable.
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still much to be done."
It should be mentioned that the unemployed are still facing numerous obstacles to access to employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it particularly difficult to return to the world of work and that “constitute the crux of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
Those are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those who are not mentioned; the mentality of the people advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Entreprendre association for the Cité noted that the directors surveyed have "a level of knowledge about low disabilities", with an "excessive representation of people in wheelchairs, physical or intellectually deficient".
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% disabled workers, a goal that was set in a law of... 1987.
According to the latest available figures, dating back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
"We now reach around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting the contributions of companies that do not respect this law.
The test: the number of establishment "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated great pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with 20 to 49 workers have disabled employees, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 workers.
